  "prompt": "In the MCU, why do people, particually in the Netflix shows, not believe in superpowered individuals?",
  "response": "In the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU), particularly in the Netflix shows like Daredevil, Jessica Jones, Luke Cage, and Iron Fist, the disbelief or skepticism about superpowered individuals stems from a few key factors:\n\n1. Localization: Unlike the Avengers who operate on a global or city-wide scale, these street-level heroes primarily work in specific neighborhoods of New York City, making their actions less visible to the general public.\n\n2. Scale of Powers: Compared to Thor, Iron Man, or the Hulk, these street-level heroes have more subtle and less flashy abilities, making them easier to dismiss or rationalize.\n\n3. Media Portrayal: Often, these characters operate in the shadows and try to keep a low profile, so media coverage is limited.\n\n4. Aftermath of New York Battle: While the Battle of New York (in The Avengers) made superhuman abilities more known, many people still view it as a distant, extraordinary event.\n\n5. Realistic Tone: The Netflix shows intentionally have a more grounded, realistic approach to storytelling, which means characters react more skeptically to extraordinary claims.\n\n6. Fear and Mistrust: Many people are naturally skeptical of extraordinary claims and may attribute superhuman abilities to luck, skill, or exaggeration.\n\nThis skepticism gradually changes as more evidence of enhanced individuals becomes apparent throughout the series.",
